00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:04.490
All right, so how do we
go about determining

00:09:04.490 --> 00:09:07.140
hybridization in complex
molecules?

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:10.780
It's actually incredibly simple,
and all that you need

00:09:10.780 --> 00:09:13.930
to do is think about for the
given atom that you're looking

00:09:13.930 --> 00:09:17.230
at, what you want to do is add
up the number of atoms that

00:09:17.230 --> 00:09:19.460
are bonded to your central
atom, or the atom you're

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:23.260
considering, and add to that
the number of lone pairs.

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:25.710
And what you end up with is the
number of hybrid orbitals

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:26.650
that you need.

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:29.760
All right, so the theory behind
hybridization and

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:31.910
