00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:07.760
We know that any time we have a
double bond it's made up of

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:10.910
one sigma bond plus
one pi bond.

00:13:10.910 --> 00:13:14.710
So, when we look at the carbon
again, that's 2 s p 2.

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:17.170
But what about the oxygen,
what's the hybridization of

00:13:17.170 --> 00:13:20.490
this oxygen atom?

00:13:20.490 --> 00:13:22.790
S p 2.

00:13:22.790 --> 00:13:26.270
So we're going to have carbon
2 s p 2, and then

00:13:26.270 --> 00:13:28.060
oxygen 2 s p 2.

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:32.590
It's s p 2 because the oxygen is
bonded to one atom plus two

00:13:32.590 --> 00:13:34.000
lone pairs, so we're going
to have a total of

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:35.060
three hybrid orbitals.

00:13:35.060 --> 00:13:38.260
All right, so this is not our
only bond, we have a double

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:40.990
bond, so we also need to
talk about the pi bond.

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:44.270
So if we talk about the pi bond,
we can say that's carbon

00:13:44.270 --> 00:13:47.100
2 p y, then the oxygen 2 p y.

00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:49.910
We could alternatively say, and
be correct, that it was

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:52.840
the carbon 2 p x and
the oxygen 2 p x.

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:54.240
Either one of those is fine.

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:57.920
All right, so that's an example
of how we can assign

00:13:57.920 --> 00:14:01.000
very quickly and very easily
what the hybridization is of a

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.290
given atom.

00:14:02.290 --> 00:14:05.890
And then also fully describe the
symmetry and the atomic or

00:14:05.890 --> 00:14:08.120
hybrid orbitals that
make up bonds.

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:10.600
So this is a lot of your
