00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:57.700
1 s.

00:23:57.700 --> 00:23:58.420
All right, great.

00:23:58.420 --> 00:24:00.870
So let's take a look at another
one, let's look again

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:04.340
at carbon b, but now let's talk
about it bonding to its

00:24:04.340 --> 00:24:06.200
oxygen there.

00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:08.730
So again, are we going
to be talking about a

00:24:08.730 --> 00:24:11.710
sigma or a pi bond?

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:16.110
A sigma bond, because again,
it's a single bond here.

00:24:16.110 --> 00:24:21.880
So what we'll say again is
carbon 2 s p 3, and let's take

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:24.930
a look at this oxygen
that it's bound to.

00:24:24.930 --> 00:24:28.530
Is this oxygen -- what is the
hybridization of this oxygen

00:24:28.530 --> 00:24:30.980
right here?

00:24:30.980 --> 00:24:32.850
What is it?

00:24:32.850 --> 00:24:35.010
OK, good, it's s p 3.

00:24:35.010 --> 00:24:38.160
It's bound to two atoms, plus it
has two lone pairs, that's

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:39.980
a total of four things.

00:24:39.980 --> 00:24:42.950
So it needs to have three
different hybrid orbitals, so

00:24:42.950 --> 00:24:51.150
we'll say it's oxygen 2 s p 3.

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:53.980
So let's skip to a different
carbon now, let's talk about

00:24:53.980 --> 00:24:58.550
carbon d, specifically the
carbon d oxygen bond.

00:24:58.550 --> 00:25:01.030
So let's do a clicker question
for this one.

00:25:01.030 --> 00:25:04.510
Let's get into the 90's, if you
