00:27:40.330 --> 00:27:41.490
in your problem-set.

00:27:41.490 --> 00:27:43.920
Does anyone have any questions
about figuring out

00:27:43.920 --> 00:27:44.580
hybridization?

00:27:44.580 --> 00:27:44.810
Yes?

00:27:44.810 --> 00:27:48.750
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:48.750 --> 00:27:52.450
PROFESSOR: I'm sorry,
what is that?

00:27:52.450 --> 00:27:54.200
In this bond here?

00:27:54.200 --> 00:27:55.310
Oh, OK, that's a
good question.

00:27:55.310 --> 00:27:57.740
So the question was why is there
not hybridization in

00:27:57.740 --> 00:27:59.290
these p orbitals here.

00:27:59.290 --> 00:28:03.250
So in order to form a double
bond, we need to have a pi

00:28:03.250 --> 00:28:05.060
bond forms, and a pi
bond forms from two

00:28:05.060 --> 00:28:06.720
unhybridized p orbitals.

00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:09.640
And if you can kind of picture
those p orbitals, if our

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:12.170
molecules are this way and
they're coming up here, we

00:28:12.170 --> 00:28:14.530
need to have electron density
above the bond

00:28:14.530 --> 00:28:15.710
and below the bond.

00:28:15.710 --> 00:28:18.000
So if they're hybrid, then
they're going to be spread out

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.120
into that tetrahedral
geometry.

00:28:20.120 --> 00:28:23.130
We want to have them parallel to
each other and they need to

00:28:23.130 --> 00:28:25.420
be the p bonds, they need
to be the p orbitals.

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:28.440
Does that makes sense?

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:33.330
So any time we have a double
bond, the pi part of the bond

00:28:33.330 --> 00:28:34.100
is going to be p orbitals.

00:28:34.100 --> 00:28:34.180
Yes?

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:34.740
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:34.740 --> 00:28:38.360
PROFESSOR: No, absolutely not.

00:28:38.360 --> 00:28:42.490
It would be absolutely correct
to put 2 p x and 2 p x here,

00:28:42.490 --> 00:28:45.130
you just can't put z, because
that's the one that's going to

00:28:45.130 --> 00:28:46.660
be involved in the sigma bond.

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:49.740
And the other important thing
is if you do put x for one,

00:28:49.740 --> 00:28:52.010
you have to make sure you put
x in the other, because they

00:28:52.010 --> 00:28:54.470
do need to be able to interact
with each other.

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:57.490
You can't have one x and one y,
but sure, you can have both

00:28:57.490 --> 00:29:02.160
x or both y.

00:29:02.160 --> 00:29:05.240
OK, so let's shift gears a
little bit and start talking

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:11.120
about bonding in terms of
chemical reactions.

00:29:11.120 --> 00:29:13.820
So we're going to start today
with talking about bond

00:29:13.820 --> 00:29:19.760
energies, and also something
called bond enthalpies.

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:22.310
And the first point is just to
bring us back to something

00:29:22.310 --> 00:29:23.490
we're very familiar with.

00:29:23.490 --> 00:29:26.580
When we talked about covalent
bonding, a concept that we

00:29:26.580 --> 00:29:29.930
have been discussing is bond
dissociation energy.

00:29:29.930 --> 00:29:33.210
That's just the energy that's
required to put into a

00:29:33.210 --> 00:29:35.590
molecule in order to
break that bond.

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:38.570
This is something that we saw
when we were talking just at

00:29:38.570 --> 00:29:41.410
the very beginning of our
unit on covalent bonds.

00:29:41.410 --> 00:29:45.450
That energy difference is the
energy difference between when

00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:49.180
we have the c h 4, if we're
talking about methane, versus

00:29:49.180 --> 00:29:52.460
one of those hydrogen bonds
breaking, one of those c h

00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:53.800
bonds breaking.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:58.080
So we've talked in the past
about bond energy, but what I

00:29:58.080 --> 00:30:01.560
want to introduce to you today
is a very related concept,

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:03.380
which is called bond enthalpy.

00:30:03.380 --> 00:30:08.400
So that's delta h here is what
we call bond enthalpy.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:10.870
So, this is talking about
instead of the change of

00:30:10.870 --> 00:30:14.380
energy accompanied with a bond
breaking, we're talking about

00:30:14.380 --> 00:30:17.350
a change in heat accompanied
with a bond breaking.

00:30:17.350 --> 00:30:20.920
So whether when that bond breaks
it requires heat, or

00:30:20.920 --> 00:30:24.310
whether it gives off heat when
you break that bond or talking

00:30:24.310 --> 00:30:25.060
about a reaction.

00:30:25.060 --> 00:30:26.250
That's what we're talking
about when we're

00:30:26.250 --> 00:30:28.770
talking about enthalpy.

00:30:28.770 --> 00:30:31.690
It turns out that enthalpy is,
in fact, very related to

00:30:31.690 --> 00:30:35.350
energy, and we can relate it
with this equation here that

00:30:35.350 --> 00:30:39.420
bond enthalpy is equal to bond
energy plus the change in

00:30:39.420 --> 00:30:41.350
pressure times volume.

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:44.120
So we could, in fact, go back
and forth between bond

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:47.670
energies and bond enthalpies,
but the reality is if we're

00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:50.970
talking about gases, which we
are in many cases, then what

00:30:50.970 --> 00:30:54.100
we find is the difference
between bond enthalpy and bond

00:30:54.100 --> 00:30:57.000
energy is only 1% to 2%.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:58.770
So it's not very significant.

00:30:58.770 --> 00:31:02.390
And, in fact, if we're talking
about solids or liquids, now

00:31:02.390 --> 00:31:05.460
we can say that the difference
between bond energy and bond

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:07.910
enthalpy is going to
be negligible.

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:11.410
So, for the rest of this class
today, we're going to stop

00:31:11.410 --> 00:31:13.880
talking about bond energy, which
I did just for a moment,

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:16.880
to orient you back to a
discussion that was familiar,

00:31:16.880 --> 00:31:19.770
we're going to switch our
discussion to bond enthalpies.

00:31:19.770 --> 00:31:22.780
One reason that we like to
talk about enthalpies is

00:31:22.780 --> 00:31:26.040
unlike energy, which can be a
little bit more tricky, bond

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:27.970
enthalpies are easy
to measure.

00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:31.330
It's easy to measure how much
heat a reaction gives off or

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:35.790
how much heat a reaction
takes in.

00:31:35.790 --> 00:31:38.550
So we can also talk about
something, which is called the

00:31:38.550 --> 00:31:42.020
standard bond enthalpy, so any
time you see this symbol here,

00:31:42.020 --> 00:31:45.110
which looks like a knot, so it
looks like a delta h knot,

00:31:45.110 --> 00:31:48.110
that refers to the standard
bond enthalpy.

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:50.680
Any time we we're talking about
a standard, whether it's

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:53.900
enthalpy or, as we'll see in
the next lecture, standard

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:57.680
entropy or a standard free
energy, we're just saying that

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:00.450
the molecules that we're talking
about are in their

00:32:00.450 --> 00:32:03.440
standard states, which means
they're in their pure form.

00:32:03.440 --> 00:32:05.850
If they're a gas it means
they're at one bar.

00:32:05.850 --> 00:32:07.740
Usually this is referring
to room

00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:11.070
temperature, so 298 kelvin.

00:32:11.070 --> 00:32:14.570
It's often that when you look
up tables of different bond

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:17.215
enthalpies, you'll see them in
their standard state and it

00:32:17.215 --> 00:32:18.710
will be at room temperature.

00:32:18.710 --> 00:32:21.830
So if we talk about standard
bond enthalpy, let's talk

00:32:21.830 --> 00:32:24.450
about what this is for these
c h bonds, which

00:32:24.450 --> 00:32:26.280
we just saw in methane.

00:32:26.280 --> 00:32:29.820
So if we're going from c h 4 to
breaking one of these c h

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:32.990
bonds, what we see is that
the bond enthalpy is 438

00:32:32.990 --> 00:32:33.640
kilojoules per mole.

00:32:33.640 --> 00:32:37.650
The fact that it's positive
tells us that we need to put

00:32:37.650 --> 00:32:40.090
in that much heat into
the system in order

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:42.240
to break that bond.

00:32:42.240 --> 00:32:45.060
So we now know the enthalpy of
a c h bond, but, of course,

00:32:45.060 --> 00:32:47.520
methane is not the only
kind of c h bond

00:32:47.520 --> 00:32:48.850
that you can envision.

00:32:48.850 --> 00:32:52.180
We could talk about the c h
bond, for example, in ethane

00:32:52.180 --> 00:32:56.650
or trifluoromethane or trichloro
or tribromomethane,

00:32:56.650 --> 00:32:59.570
and what you'll find is that
the amount of enthalpy that

00:32:59.570 --> 00:33:03.140
that reaction is associated with
depends on the exact type

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:06.470
of c h bond that you have. So,
for example, we can see that

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:09.060
we have slightly different,
not vastly different, but

00:33:09.060 --> 00:33:12.690
slightly different changes in
enthalpy depending on which

00:33:12.690 --> 00:33:17.090
kind of c h bond that
were breaking.

00:33:17.090 --> 00:33:19.570
And what I want to point out
also is that all of these

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:21.690
delta h's, all of these
standard bond

00:33:21.690 --> 00:33:23.580
enthalpies are positive.

00:33:23.580 --> 00:33:27.420
Any time we have a positive
delta h, we call this an

00:33:27.420 --> 00:33:29.320
endothermic reaction.

00:33:29.320 --> 00:33:32.080
And again, endothermic
just means that the

00:33:32.080 --> 00:33:34.380
reaction takes in energy.

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:37.220
It's very similar to what when
we're talking about energy

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:40.125
whether something's taken in
or released, whether it's

00:33:40.125 --> 00:33:41.060
positive or negative.

00:33:41.060 --> 00:33:44.510
If you have positive delta h,
it's endothermic, it takes in

00:33:44.510 --> 00:33:48.040
heat in order for the
reaction to go.

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:50.830
So we can think about instead of
talking about all of these

00:33:50.830 --> 00:33:54.840
individual c h bonds, instead
we can talk about what the

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:57.090
average value would be
for all c h bonds.

00:33:57.090 --> 00:34:00.610
So we can say that the average
of any c h bond is 412

00:34:00.610 --> 00:34:02.010
kilojoules per mole.

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:04.360
So you can imagine if you're
looking these things up in

00:34:04.360 --> 00:34:06.910
terms of a reference table or
maybe in the appendix of your

00:34:06.910 --> 00:34:10.140
textbook, it would be an
impossibly huge number of

00:34:10.140 --> 00:34:13.630
pages to write every single
different kinds of c h bond.

00:34:13.630 --> 00:34:16.650
So that's why instead they talk
about the average bond

00:34:16.650 --> 00:34:17.680
enthalpies.

00:34:17.680 --> 00:34:21.370
So for c h, again, that's 412,
and all of the enthalpies we

00:34:21.370 --> 00:34:24.360
just saw fall within
about 8% of that.

00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:27.710
And in your book you can look
up any type of bond that's

00:34:27.710 --> 00:34:28.680
listed here.

00:34:28.680 --> 00:34:30.840
So we saw c h is 412.

00:34:30.840 --> 00:34:34.110
You can look up a c c bond, you
can look up a c c double

00:34:34.110 --> 00:34:36.610
bond, a c c triple
bond, and so on.

00:34:36.610 --> 00:34:39.270
And you'll note that what
these are are mean bond

00:34:39.270 --> 00:34:41.990
enthalpies, so they're the
average of all different types

00:34:41.990 --> 00:34:47.300
of c h bonds or c c bonds
that you can imagine.

00:34:47.300 --> 00:34:50.360
So, you might be asking what's
so important about being able

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:52.710
to look up and think about
these different bond

00:34:52.710 --> 00:34:53.670
enthalpies.

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:55.890
And the reason that it's
important is because if you're

00:34:55.890 --> 00:34:58.660
looking at a reaction, no matter
how complicated that

00:34:58.660 --> 00:35:02.540
reaction is, you can actually
figure out what the enthalpy

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:06.210
of the entire reaction is by
adding up all the individual

00:35:06.210 --> 00:35:09.720
mean bond enthalpies of the
products, and all the

00:35:09.720 --> 00:35:12.760
individual mean bond enthalpies
of their reactants

00:35:12.760 --> 00:35:15.480
and thinking about the
difference between those two.

00:35:15.480 --> 00:35:18.240
So we'll do that in just a
second, and the reaction that

00:35:18.240 --> 00:35:21.330
we'll do it with is the
oxidation of glucose here.

00:35:21.330 --> 00:35:26.733
So, c 6 h 12 o 6, one mole of
glucose plus six moles of

00:35:26.733 --> 00:35:29.610
oxygen, gives us six moles
of carbon dioxide and

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:31.320
six moles of water.

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:34.310
So what we can find out, and
hopefully what we will match

00:35:34.310 --> 00:35:37.700
up when we look at using the
different bond enthalpies, is

00:35:37.700 --> 00:35:41.250
that the enthalpy of this entire
reaction is negative

00:35:41.250 --> 00:35:44.220
2816 kilojoules per mole.

00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:47.200
So in this case we're saying
that delta h is negative.

00:35:47.200 --> 00:35:48.400
Does anyone know what
it's called

00:35:48.400 --> 00:35:51.030
when delta h is negative?

00:35:51.030 --> 00:35:52.280
Everyone knows, great.

00:35:52.280 --> 00:35:52.960
So it's exothermic.

00:35:52.960 --> 00:35:56.500
This is an exothermic reaction,
the reaction

00:35:56.500 --> 00:35:59.870
releases heat.

00:35:59.870 --> 00:36:02.420
So I just want to mention before
we go on, if you look

00:36:02.420 --> 00:36:06.060
at almost any freshman chemistry
textbook, what

00:36:06.060 --> 00:36:09.910
you'll find is this oxidation of
glucose reaction is used a

00:36:09.910 --> 00:36:12.820
lot in talking about
thermochemistry.

00:36:12.820 --> 00:36:14.920
And one reason it's talked about
is because it's very

00:36:14.920 --> 00:36:17.070
convenient to talk about
something where we start with

00:36:17.070 --> 00:36:21.120
one mole of glucose and end up
with 12 moles of products.

00:36:21.120 --> 00:36:23.290
That's going to be helpful what
we're doing a practice

00:36:23.290 --> 00:36:25.740
problem to see exactly how you
deal with it when there's

00:36:25.740 --> 00:36:27.330
different numbers of moles.

00:36:27.330 --> 00:36:29.570
But the other reason you always
see this reaction is

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:32.030
because it's an incredibly
important reaction.

00:36:32.030 --> 00:36:34.840
The oxidation of glucose is
going on all the time in our

00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:39.620
body, this is our main source
of energy for all animals.

00:36:39.620 --> 00:36:42.600
So let's think a little bit
about why this reaction is so

00:36:42.600 --> 00:36:44.170
important and so prevalent.

00:36:44.170 --> 00:36:46.950
It turns out that if we're
talking about plants, plants

00:36:46.950 --> 00:36:48.620
do the reverse reaction.

00:36:48.620 --> 00:36:52.130
So plants take carbon dioxide
and water and they turn it

00:36:52.130 --> 00:36:55.720
into glucose or energy for us,
energy stored in the bonds of

00:36:55.720 --> 00:36:58.850
glucose plus oxygen.

00:36:58.850 --> 00:37:01.220
So if we do the reverse
reaction, this is actually

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:02.960
going to require energy.

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:06.080
Where do plants get
this energy?

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:07.520
Yeah, this is just
photosynthesis here.

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:10.430
This is the photosynthesis
where plants are turning

00:37:10.430 --> 00:37:15.120
carbon dioxide and water into
sugar and into oxygen.

00:37:15.120 --> 00:37:17.990
So what happens when we eat
the plants or when we eat

00:37:17.990 --> 00:37:21.080
animals that have eaten the
plants is that we perform the

00:37:21.080 --> 00:37:23.990
reverse reaction now, which is
what I just showed you, the

00:37:23.990 --> 00:37:24.660
oxidation of glucose.

00:37:24.660 --> 00:37:29.230
And even though it's not the
products of the reaction that

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:32.070
are particularly valuable to us,
we just breathe out the c

00:37:32.070 --> 00:37:36.040
o 2, and actually we'd rather
have less of that than more in

00:37:36.040 --> 00:37:40.640
our environment, but what's
important here is instead the

00:37:40.640 --> 00:37:43.990
energy or the enthalpy that's
given often in this reaction.

00:37:43.990 --> 00:37:47.240
So as I said, this reaction
has a negative enthalpy of

00:37:47.240 --> 00:37:49.920
2816 kilojoules per mole.

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:52.560
That's a lot of enthalpy
and a lot of energy.

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:56.170
So we actually end up using that
energy to fuel most of

00:37:56.170 --> 00:37:57.610
what is going on
in our bodies.

00:37:57.610 --> 00:38:01.400
So instead of storing it as
sugar, once we oxidize the

00:38:01.400 --> 00:38:05.240
sugar, now we just store it as
ATP, and as you know, ATP is

00:38:05.240 --> 00:38:07.480
the currency of energy
in the cells.

00:38:07.480 --> 00:38:10.350
So this is why you see this
reaction again and again and

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:12.630
again in just about any
chemistry textbook that you

00:38:12.630 --> 00:38:15.040
open up as sort of a
general reaction.

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:17.920
The reason it's used is it's
just so important and so

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:21.930
prevalent in terms of thinking
about our bodies and how we're

00:38:21.930 --> 00:38:24.890
staying alive and
using energy.

00:38:24.890 --> 00:38:27.240
All right, so let's go ahead and
use this as an example of

00:38:27.240 --> 00:38:30.170
what we just said, which is
using the bond enthalpies of

00:38:30.170 --> 00:38:34.750
the products and the reactants
to figure out the enthalpy of

00:38:34.750 --> 00:38:36.620
the entire reaction.

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:39.830
So the way that we do this
is we add up all of the

00:38:39.830 --> 00:38:43.520
individual mean bond enthalpies
of the reactants,

00:38:43.520 --> 00:38:46.940
and we subtract from that all
of the individual bond

00:38:46.940 --> 00:38:49.700
enthalpies of the products.

00:38:49.700 --> 00:38:51.830
So we can think about what
this will tell us.

00:38:51.830 --> 00:38:55.570
If you think about the fact if
the bonds are stronger in the

00:38:55.570 --> 00:38:59.350
products than they were in the
reactants, you can go ahead

00:38:59.350 --> 00:39:01.430
and click in and tell me if
you think we'll have a

00:39:01.430 --> 00:39:04.490
negative or a positive
delta h here.

00:39:04.490 --> 00:39:31.090
All right, let's take 10
more seconds on this.

00:39:31.090 --> 00:39:38.250
OK, great, so negative is
correct and some people got

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:39.090
totally mixed up.

00:39:39.090 --> 00:39:40.940
Didn't just get one thing --
so let's just focus on the

00:39:40.940 --> 00:39:42.900
right answer to start with.

00:39:42.900 --> 00:39:45.070
The correct answer is that
it's negative, it's an

00:39:45.070 --> 00:39:47.400
exothermic reaction.

00:39:47.400 --> 00:39:49.000
And actually, lets switch
to our class

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:50.420
notes to explain why.

00:39:50.420 --> 00:39:53.040
And also, this was the quiz
