00:39:57.990 --> 00:40:00.620
But let's still focus on the
right answer here and see why

00:40:00.620 --> 00:40:01.680
it's correct.

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:04.750
So if we're talking about the
bonds being stronger in the

00:40:04.750 --> 00:40:09.290
products, that basically means
that we ended up releasing a

00:40:09.290 --> 00:40:12.340
lot of heat when we made those
bonds and the products, and we

00:40:12.340 --> 00:40:15.000
didn't have to use up too much
of that heat to break all the

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:16.380
bonds and the reactants.

00:40:16.380 --> 00:40:18.190
So that's why we say
that delta h

00:40:18.190 --> 00:40:19.340
is going to be negative.

00:40:19.340 --> 00:40:23.490
You could also just do it not
conceptually, just plugging it

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:25.920
into the equation, but it's
better to kind of understand

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:27.490
exactly why that is.

00:40:27.490 --> 00:40:30.960
It's because it takes more
energy -- you gain more energy

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:32.970
forming the products
than you take

00:40:32.970 --> 00:40:34.580
breaking up the reactants.

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:37.320
So if we have the opposite case
here, if the bonds are

00:40:37.320 --> 00:40:40.430
stronger in the reactants, now
what we're going to find is

00:40:40.430 --> 00:40:43.750
that the delta h of the reaction
is positive and what

00:40:43.750 --> 00:40:49.590
you're dealing with is an
endothermic reaction.

00:40:49.590 --> 00:40:52.200
So let's go ahead and do this
with our example of the

00:40:52.200 --> 00:40:54.320
oxidation of glucose.

00:40:54.320 --> 00:40:57.210
So, I've just written out the
glucose molecule so you can

00:40:57.210 --> 00:41:01.055
see all of its individual bonds
here since we're going

00:41:01.055 --> 00:41:04.210
to be using that information.

00:41:04.210 --> 00:41:06.610
So let's start by talking
about the bonds that are

00:41:06.610 --> 00:41:10.040
broken in terms of thinking
about all of

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:11.420
the reactants here.

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:14.800
So if we're talking about the
sugar molecule itself, what we

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:18.090
have is we have seven
c h bonds.

00:41:18.090 --> 00:41:22.400
And if we add up all the o h
bonds, we have five of those.

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:27.790
How many c o single
bonds do we have?

00:41:27.790 --> 00:41:29.690
What do people think?

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:32.030
Yeah. five c o single bonds.

00:41:32.030 --> 00:41:36.890
What about c c single bonds?
five of those as well.

00:41:36.890 --> 00:41:39.610
C o double bonds?

00:41:39.610 --> 00:41:41.360
Just one c o double bond.

00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:44.070
And then we have our oxygen
molecule to worry about and we

00:41:44.070 --> 00:41:47.150
have six o o double bonds.

00:41:47.150 --> 00:41:49.810
So if we add up all of the
bonds are broken, and we

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:52.780
subtract from that the bonds
that are formed, those

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:57.650
strengths, the c double bond
o, we have 12 of those.

00:41:57.650 --> 00:42:01.200
And how many o h bonds
do we have?

00:42:01.200 --> 00:42:02.960
Right, 12 as well.

00:42:02.960 --> 00:42:07.290
So if we add up all the bonds
broken, what we end up with is

00:42:07.290 --> 00:42:11.790
12,452 kilojoules per mole,
and it's talking about per

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:14.350
mole of glucose that's
oxidized.

00:42:14.350 --> 00:42:17.850
And in terms of bonds formed,
what we see is 15,192

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:21.740
kilojoules per mole.

00:42:21.740 --> 00:42:27.190
So all we need to do to figure
out the change in enthalpy,

00:42:27.190 --> 00:42:30.380
and when it has this subscript
r here, I meant to mention,

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:32.740
that means the enthalpy
for the reaction.

00:42:32.740 --> 00:42:38.290
We just subtract these bonds
here from the ones that we

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:40.480
ended up forming.

00:42:40.480 --> 00:42:44.570
So basically, what we're saying
-- excuse me, these are

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:45.660
the ones that we broke.

00:42:45.660 --> 00:42:51.480
It's 12,452 minus 15,192,
which we formed.

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:55.370
So we end up with an enthalpy of
reaction of negative 2,740

00:42:55.370 --> 00:43:01.090
kilojoules per mole of glucose
that's oxidized.

00:43:01.090 --> 00:43:03.570
All right, so if you remember
the number that I told you

00:43:03.570 --> 00:43:08.240
before, it doesn't exactly match
up with what we had said

00:43:08.240 --> 00:43:09.250
