00:43:09.250 --> 00:43:12.400
The exact number is 2,816.

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:15.200
It is within 3% though,
that's pretty good.

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:18.020
Because remember, we're not
using exact bond enthalpies

00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:21.160
here, what we were using is
average bond enthalpies.

00:43:21.160 --> 00:43:24.180
So it makes sense that we're
going to be a little bit off.

00:43:24.180 --> 00:43:27.610
But if all you have in front of
you is the information on

00:43:27.610 --> 00:43:30.270
bond enthalpies, mean bond
enthalpies, this is a great

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:33.530
way to figure out the enthalpy
of an overall reaction.

00:43:33.530 --> 00:43:35.990
We can think of a different way,
however, to think about

00:43:35.990 --> 00:43:38.460
the enthalpy of an overall
reaction, and this is talking

00:43:38.460 --> 00:43:41.460
about the heat of formation.

00:43:41.460 --> 00:43:45.680
And the heat of formation or
delta h formation here is

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:49.680
equal to the heat of -- or the
enthalpy of reaction, if we're

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:54.420
talking about forming one mole
of compound from its pure

00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:56.850
elements, which are in their
standard states.

00:43:56.850 --> 00:43:59.340
So basically, there's a table
that you can look up which

00:43:59.340 --> 00:44:02.770
tells you the enthalpy of
formation for any compound

00:44:02.770 --> 00:44:05.100
that you're interested in, and
this is actually an appendix

00:44:05.100 --> 00:44:08.340
to of your textbooks, and you
will need to use this to solve

00:44:08.340 --> 00:44:10.630
your problems on p-set.

00:44:10.630 --> 00:44:14.390
But let me say that, for
example, if we're talking

00:44:14.390 --> 00:44:18.170
about water here, that's formed
from hydrogen and

00:44:18.170 --> 00:44:20.390
oxygen, if we're talking about
the elements in their pure

00:44:20.390 --> 00:44:26.050
forms at one bar, standard
states, and room temperature.

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:28.600
And if we look this up in our
textbook, we would find that

00:44:28.600 --> 00:44:32.610
the delta h of formation for
water is negative 286

00:44:32.610 --> 00:44:35.800
kilojoules per mole.

00:44:35.800 --> 00:44:38.440
Similarly we can look up the
