00:45:37.370 --> 00:45:40.410
So let's go ahead and solve a
problem actually using the

00:45:40.410 --> 00:45:42.030
delta h's of formation.

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:45.100
Let's see if we can do any
better to coming close to the

00:45:45.100 --> 00:45:47.620
reality for the oxidation
of glucose.

00:45:47.620 --> 00:45:50.970
So if we're going to calculate
the delta h for the reaction

00:45:50.970 --> 00:45:54.500
for the oxidation of glucose,
or actually for any reaction

00:45:54.500 --> 00:45:58.370
at all, what we want to do is
take the delta h of formation

00:45:58.370 --> 00:46:02.280
of the products and subtract
from that the delta h of

00:46:02.280 --> 00:46:03.340
formation of the reactants.

00:46:03.340 --> 00:46:08.000
So let's go ahead and do that.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:12.940
And in terms of talking about
the oxidation of glucose, if

00:46:12.940 --> 00:46:19.410
we talk about delta h of this
reaction, what we need to take

00:46:19.410 --> 00:46:25.350
is 6 times delta h of formation
of c o 2, since

00:46:25.350 --> 00:46:28.450
we're forming, that's in our
products, we're forming six

00:46:28.450 --> 00:46:30.780
moles of c o 2.

00:46:30.780 --> 00:46:38.120
Plus 6 times delta h formation
of h 2 o, since we're forming

00:46:38.120 --> 00:46:41.510
six moles of h 2 o.

00:46:41.510 --> 00:46:45.450
And we subtract from that the
heat of formation of all of

00:46:45.450 --> 00:46:47.260
our reactants.

00:46:47.260 --> 00:46:51.640
So we only have one mole, so we
just say delta h formation

00:46:51.640 --> 00:46:59.770
of c 6 h 12 o 6, and then in
addition to that we have six

00:46:59.770 --> 00:47:07.760
moles delta h formation
of oxygen, of o 2.

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:10.030
All right, so this is our
equation here and at this

00:47:10.030 --> 00:47:13.310
point what we would do is we
would look up what all of the

00:47:13.310 --> 00:47:17.150
delta h formation values
are for c o 2, h 2

00:47:17.150 --> 00:47:21.720
o, sugar, and oxygen.

00:47:21.720 --> 00:47:27.910
So what we would find is that
we end up having 6 times

00:47:27.910 --> 00:47:30.150
negative 393 .

00:47:30.150 --> 00:47:32.530
5 -- that's what we had
just looked up and

00:47:32.530 --> 00:47:35.030
told you for c o 2.

00:47:35.030 --> 00:47:39.280
Plus 6 times negative 285 .

00:47:39.280 --> 00:47:41.400
8 for the water.

00:47:41.400 --> 00:47:51.200
Minus 1 times 1260, so
it's negative 1260

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:54.430
for our sugar here.

00:47:54.430 --> 00:47:57.570
And then what we're going to end
up with is having minus,

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:00.270
and what is it for
oxygen again?

00:48:00.270 --> 00:48:03.220
So minus 0.

00:48:03.220 --> 00:48:06.620
So what we end up with in terms
of the delta h for the

00:48:06.620 --> 00:48:10.820
entire reaction here, is we end
up with negative 2816, and

00:48:10.820 --> 00:48:21.920
it's going to be kilojoules
per mole of glucose.

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:25.960
All right, so let's see how this
matches up, and hopefully

00:48:25.960 --> 00:48:28.860
you can actually remember that
this matches up actually

00:48:28.860 --> 00:48:30.510
perfectly here.

00:48:30.510 --> 00:48:34.450
So what we are going to see
is that, in fact, what we

00:48:34.450 --> 00:48:36.630
calculated versus what
is experimental

00:48:36.630 --> 00:48:38.100
is dead-on the same.

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:40.630
So there's actually one more
way to figure out the

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:42.780
enthalpies of a reaction,
I'm going to go over

00:48:42.780 --> 00:48:44.510
it just very briefly.

00:48:44.510 --> 00:48:47.510
And that's based on the fact
that enthalpy is a state

00:48:47.510 --> 00:48:51.280
function, and by state function
what I mean is that

00:48:51.280 --> 00:48:56.220
it doesn't matter how you got
from point a to point b, all

00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:58.740
that matters is the difference
between the two.

00:48:58.740 --> 00:49:02.030
So another example of a state
function is altitude, for

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:03.120
example, on a mountain.

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:06.440
So if you're talking about
altitude, you go from point a

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:11.060
to point b on the mountain, and
it doesn't matter how you

00:49:11.060 --> 00:49:13.960
got there -- you could have
climbed all the way up the top

00:49:13.960 --> 00:49:16.050
of the mountain, then went
back down and eventually

00:49:16.050 --> 00:49:17.400
landed on point b.

00:49:17.400 --> 00:49:18.990
Or you could have gone
straight from

00:49:18.990 --> 00:49:20.630
point a to point b.

00:49:20.630 --> 00:49:24.000
The change in altitude between
point a and point b do not

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.890
depend on the path, they're
independent of path.

00:49:26.890 --> 00:49:29.960
So this difference right here
does not matter on how you got

00:49:29.960 --> 00:49:32.600
there, it does not make a
difference how you got there,

00:49:32.600 --> 00:49:35.650
altitude is a state function.

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:38.810
So similarly, we can say that
enthalpy is a state function

00:49:38.810 --> 00:49:43.290
as well, if we're talking about
part reaction a here,

00:49:43.290 --> 00:49:47.770
which has our reactants going
to our products in 2 b here.

00:49:47.770 --> 00:49:49.900
It doesn't matter how
we got there.

00:49:49.900 --> 00:49:52.550
We can actually calculate the
change in enthalpy at all

00:49:52.550 --> 00:49:53.860
different points here.

00:49:53.860 --> 00:49:56.840
All that we actually have to
worry about at the end of the

00:49:56.840 --> 00:49:59.510
day is the difference
between a and b.

00:49:59.510 --> 00:50:02.320
So that's what we mean
by state function.

